Distributed consensus algorithms like Raft and Paxos solve the fundamental problem of getting multiple servers to agree on a sequence of values despite network partitions and server failures. Raft divides the consensus problem into leader election, log replication, and safety guarantees. A cluster of N servers can tolerate up to (N-1)/2 failures while maintaining consistency. The leader accepts client requests, appends them to its log, and replicates entries to followers. Once a majority of servers have persisted an entry, it is considered committed and can be applied to the state machine. Leader election uses randomized timeouts to prevent split votes — when a follower's election timer expires without receiving a heartbeat, it becomes a candidate and requests votes from other servers. The algorithm guarantees that at most one leader exists per term, and that committed entries are never lost even if servers crash and restart.